{
  "doc_id": "33480",
  "text": "Individual somatic mutations throughout the coding region of the PIGA gene were identified in approximately 80% of our PNH patients. The majority (approximately 48%) of PIGA mutations were found on exon 2, which contains nearly a half of the coding region, although mutational hotspots were not observed. Like Nafa et al. [CITATION_1] , we frequently found small deletions or duplications/insertions in PIGA, which resulted in a frameshift in the coding region and a shortened, nonfunctional protein, except for the three missense mutations (two in exon 2 and one in exon 6). Although PIGA function is usually abrogated by these mutations, decreased PIGA activity due to missense mutations also induces PNH [CITATION_2] . Because somatic PIGA mutations occur in only one or few HSCs, clonal expansion of these HSCs is necessary to develop PNH.",
